Deep brain surgery helps 36-year-old woman move again,"After being in a vegetative state for more than a year-and-a-half, 36-year-old Bhavesha Gosrani has finally started moving her body again. Gosrani, who underwent Deep Brain Stimulation (DBS) surgery on April 3 in Jaslok Hospital, had given birth to twins in June 2016 through a c-section during which she suffered a hypoxic brain injury in the operation theatre. Due to lack of equipment in the maternity home, she was immediately shifted to a Mulund-based private hospital the next day. Gosrani was on a ventilator for 20 days and then was gradually weaned off. She was later shifted to her home but was in a vegetative state. Nikhil Gosrani, her husband, said, “She suffered from cardiorespiratory arrest on the table during the delivery of our children. Since then she never came back to normal life. For the past one-and-a-half years, Gosrani has been on medicines but in a vegetative state. We could see that she was getting emotional through her eyes. We never wanted to give up hope on her.” After waiting for her condition to improve naturally for a few months, she was taken to Jaslok Hospital to explore further possible medical treatment. Dr Paresh Doshi, Director of Department of Neurosurgery at Jaslok Hospital said, “After a few months of wait, there were no signs of improvement due to which we decided to perform the DBS surgery as she cleared all the selection criteria for the surgery. She showed signs of arousal during the surgery. After the surgery, she has been showing some movement. She will take at least three to four months to recover well.” Meanwhile, Dr Adil Chagla, Neurosurgeon at KEM Hospital, said, “I would not recommend DBS surgery. There will be a lot of challenges since we will be stimulating the brain which can also cause a side effect. A long-term rehabilitation could also have been a possible way to help the patient.”","Bhavesha Gosrani, who had been in a vegetative state for over a year-and-a-half due to a hypoxic brain injury during childbirth in June 2016, has shown signs of improvement after undergoing Deep Brain Stimulation (DBS) surgery at Jaslok Hospital. The surgery, performed on April 3, has enabled her to start moving her body again. Her condition had not improved with medication alone, prompting the decision for DBS surgery. Doctors expect her recovery to take several months. Meanwhile, other medical experts caution about the potential risks and challenges associated with DBS surgery.",Health and Wellness,2018-04-07 00:00:00
A few undesirable habits of patients,"Often many persons ask for a medicine for a symptom without caring for the underlying disease. They continue to use the same for quite some time till the disease advances, such as in generalised weakness, cough, recurrent fevers, hoarse voice, headache, difficulty in swallowing, swelling feet, giddiness, muscular and joint pains, low vision, etc. This symptomatic casual approach to a serious underlying disease can put you in great trouble later on while to nip the same in the very beginning is a wise approach. Instructions and preventive measures along with the needed medicine, explained by the doctor, are commonly ignored by many. Steam inhalation in allergic bronchitis, proper rest and good diet in viral infections, vocal rest in voice changes, low salt intake in blood pressure and washing of hands properly before meals can keep local infections at bay. If a child is suffering from diarrhoea, etc, parents are advised not to give milk and sweets for a few days, but the mother does not feel satisfied till she feeds the child with sweetened milk though along with medicines — thus not giving the desirable results. With due precautions while working on the computer, eye stains, headache and cervical pain can well be avoided. Proper follow-up is a casualty among our patients. Once symptoms are relieved, medicines are stopped. In many such cases, diseases get suppressed but resurface after sometime. So, taking a proper dose of medicines and for the recommended period, as in the case of antibiotics, is of great importance. Many patients, especially in the rural areas, do not come forward to tell the complaints they are suffering from due to the fear that they may be having some serious disease. In the case of sexually transmitted diseases, patients are too ashamed or embarrassed to seek medical attention because of cultural taboos. Delay in handling such cases results in harmful effects. Patients often want quick relief. They frequently change the doctor, even the system of medicine. Chronic diseases such as diabetes, BP and heart problems take a long time to tame with regular and prolonged treatment. Irregular treatment for such diseases is harmful. Self-medication must be avoided. Often patients accept the substitutes of the medicines on the written prescription that may be cheap, but sometimes these may be substandard or even fake. It is better to have the same brand even if you have to go from one chemist shop to another.","Ignoring underlying diseases and relying solely on symptomatic treatment can lead to worsening health conditions. Patients often neglect preventive measures and proper follow-up, opting for quick relief and changing doctors frequently. Self-medication and accepting cheap substitutes can be harmful. Proper adherence to treatment and medical advice is crucial for maintaining health.",Health and Wellness,2011-07-13 00:00:00
