PMO steps in after BSNL puts bid on hold,"NEW DELHI: The Prime Minister’s Office (PMO) is all set to intervene in BSNL’s tender fiasco as the state-owned telco has now decided to put its 93 million lines GSM contract, the world’s largest equipment deal, ‘on hold,’ an executive with direct knowledge of the development told ET. The PMO has called for a meeting on January 6 to discuss BSNL’s performance as the telco has been losing revenues and market share — the delay in awarding contracts in the 93 million lines tender will be a primary issue on the agenda, this executive explained. According to government officials aware of the development, Prime Minister Manmohan Singh will meet communications minister A Raja, finance minister Pranab Mukherjee, department of telecom secretary PJ Thomas, top executives from BSNL including its CMD Kuldeep Goyal, executives from the Planning Commission and Knowledge Commission chairman Sam Pitroda (who is also a special advisor to the DoT) during the January 6 meeting to discuss the plight of BSNL. PlayUnmute Fullscreen BSNL has been making huge operating losses in the past two years, only managing to stay in the black because of interest income from its accumulated cash reserves. It ran out of capacity to expand cellular services nearly 18 months ago, and no new major contracts for mobile networks and equipment have been awarded in the past 24 months. On Wednesday, the PSU’s board decided to put its $10 billion tender (which has already been delayed by over an year) on hold after the Central Vigilance Commission (CVC) had launched a fresh probe into ‘irregularities’ since guidelines forbid post-tender negotiations with successful bidders. Sweden’s Ericsson had emerged as the lowest bidder in the North and South East zones while China’s Huawei was selected for the South and West Zones. Meanwhile, in a related development, the umbrella body representing all employee unions of BSNL has threatened to launch an agitation against the telco’s move to put the tender the hold. “We have gone on strike in the past against delays to expansion plans, and we will decide within the next two days if the unions will adopt a similar strategy. We have been talks with the BSNL management and the DoT on this issue and are extremely upset with the latest decision,” explained VAN Namboodiri, general secretary, BSNL employees unions. BSNL’s performance has been slipping for the last three years. In 2005, BSNL added more subscribers than Bharti Airtel and by mid-2006, it was almost within striking distance of occupying the top slot in mobile customers. BSNL’s first tender for 63 million lines in 2006, then the world’s largest, was delayed after Motorola went to court. The US-based networks company later withdrew the case, but this tender was finally reduced to a mere 13 million lines after telecoms minister A Raja intervened. To overcome this, BSNL in May 2008 floated the 93 million lines GSM tender. This time around, Nokia Siemens Networks, which was disqualified on technical grounds approached the CVC and also filed cases in multiple courts. After months of delay, in August 2009, BSNL overcame two major challenges — the ‘integrity panel’ set up with the permission from CVC as well as the Andhra Pradesh High Court ruled that the telco was justified in disqualifying NSN because it did not meet technical requirements. As reported first by ET last week, the dismal showing by BSNL in 2008-09 resulted in the telco ceding the top slot for sales and profits to private sector rival Bharti Airtel for the first time ever. It also means that BSNL’s valuations will suffer as it prepares for its first public share offering. For the year-ended March 2009, BSNL posted a net profit of Rs 574.85 crore on total revenues of Rs 35,811.92 crore. Profits had nose-dived 81% and revenues fell 6% when compared to the year-ago period. This is the second successive year that BSNL witnessed a massive fall in profits despite being one of the largest players in the world's fastest-growing telecoms market. In comparison, Bharti Airtel’s revenues grew by over Rs 10,000 crore during 2008-09 and its revenues jumped from Rs 27,012 crore for the fiscal ended March 2008 to Rs 37,352 crore for the year-ended March 2009. During this period, its profits increased to Rs 7,859 crore when compared to Rs 6,395 crore for the year-ended March 2008.","The Prime Minister’s Office is poised to address BSNL's issues as it suspends its 93 million lines GSM tender due to a fresh probe by the Central Vigilance Commission. BSNL has faced operating losses and capacity limitations, with no significant contracts awarded in 24 months. The telecom giant's performance decline led to Bharti Airtel surpassing it in sales and profits for the first time in 2008-09. BSNL's net profit fell drastically despite being a major player in India's telecom market. The PSU's decision sparked union threats of agitation, highlighting the urgency of resolving BSNL's challenges.",Technology and Gadgets,2010-01-01 00:00:00
Doctors struggle to cure malaria,"MUMBAI: After three bouts of malaria in 11 months, city resident Sarita Seshan has been left without a job and with scepticism of modern medicineâ€™s ability to combat malaria. Each time she came down with the infection, it took long and complicated diagnoses, and multiple rounds of different drugs before her fever finally subsided. â€œMalaria finds mention in Vedic texts of 1600 BC,â€™â€™ mused Seshan. â€œHowever, its cure, still seems a challenge.â€™â€™ Cases like hers are on the rise as treatment of malaria becomes increasingly complicated. Many of the complications stem from changes in plasmodium, the parasite that causes the disease. For one, there has been an increase in plasmodium falciparum, a species that causes cerebral malaria. Till about a decade ago, this species accounted for only 20 per cent of malaria infections in the city. Falciparum infections can be fatal. The remaining 80 per cent of malaria infections were caused by the less lethal plasmodium vivax. However, new data collected at the KEM Hospital and anecdotal evidence from private practitioners in Mumbai and Navi Mumbai indicate that falciparum now accounts for 30 to 40 per cent of malaria infections in the city. The problem is compounded by falciparumâ€™s resistance to common anti-malarial drugs. Studies from the KEM Hospital indicate that over 50 per cent of plasmodium falciparum cases in Mumbai are resistant to chloroquine, which is the first-line treatment recommended by the national malaria control programme.In addition, there have been reported cases of falciparum resistance to other common anti-malarials such as artemisinin, primaquine, sulfadoxine and pyrimethamine. Despite the steadily increasing drug resistance, public health experts do not recommend abandoning chloroquine. â€œThe majority of malaria infections in Mumbai are still caused by plasmodium vivax, which is sensitive to chloroquine,â€™â€™ explained N.A. Kshirsagar, dean of KEM Hospital. Doctors are quick to add that treatment with chloroquine demands close followup to ensure that patients.complete their full dose and that they respond adequately to the drug. However, multiple studies reveal irrational and indiscriminate use of anti-malarials. â€œPrivate doctors especially are under pressure to show quick results or else the patient will go to another physician. This market pressure coupled with patientsâ€™ often unrealistic expectations prompt doctors to switch drugs rapidly without completing full doses,â€™â€™ said Chandana Behl, private physician and a public health activist in Navi Mumbai. While resistance to existing anti-malarial drugs grows, there are few new drugs that are affordable and easy to administer. Shobhona Sharma, a molecular biologist at the Tata Institute Fundamental Research who works on malaria, added that the prospect of malaria vaccines also remains bleak because not enough is known about the workings of the pathogen. â€œMosquito nets are the best option at this stage. The idea is not to get bitten,â€™â€™ Sharma said","Malaria cases in Mumbai rise due to increasing prevalence of drug-resistant Plasmodium falciparum, causing complications and fatalities. Resistance to common anti-malarials like chloroquine poses challenges despite its continued use. Private doctors face pressure to switch drugs quickly, leading to incomplete treatments. Limited affordable alternatives and bleak prospects for malaria vaccines exacerbate the situation. Mosquito nets are recommended as the primary preventive measure.",Health and Wellness,2002-08-20 00:00:00
