This vaccine auto debunks myths and helps book slots,"Sliding through the streets of Chennai, artist Gowtham’s auto has more to it than meets the eye. The white-blue three-wheeler, which has vials and injections popping off it, is an artistic tool to spread vaccine awareness in the city.Organised in collaboration with the Greater Chennai Corporation, the auto which is dubbed the ‘vaccine auto’, debunks vaccine myths, helps senior citizens book slots, and assuages doubters, among other things.Gowtham, who was also behind the viral corona helmet of 2020, adds that he wanted to spread the message to the nooks and crannies of the city through a creative lens.“There is still a lot of doubt and questions regarding the virus. And there is also a kind of fear among most. Through this auto, we try to reach the people on the streets who have vaccine hesitancy,” Gowtham begins.As the auto zooms through the 15 zones of Chennai, it is accompanied by a speaker blasting a pre-recorded message about vaccines and its efficiency. Driven by driver Mani, the auto also has a volunteer, who steps out of the vehicle at times to clear doubts through pamphlets and interactions.What are some of the most common questions they get? “A lot of people want to know how to register on the CoWin app. We either help them with it, or redirect them to the nearest Primary Healthcare Centre. A lot of people also enquire about the interval between two doses. We also get a lot of ‘injection podanuma’ ,” adds Gowtham, with a smile.Fear is a main barrier, and the idea is to turn that fear on its head with a creative message, Gowtham adds. “When people get a visual confirmation of the same in the form of an art piece like this on moving wheels, it makes it easier to get through to them. Vaccines are a necessity today and we wanted to do this with a twist,” the artist explains.And that is not all. The vehicle is further made of plastic waste. The vaccine vial atop the auto, for instance, is an old water can. The injections are nothing but discarded pipes. “We also used waste plywood, water bottles and other forms of plastic to complete the design in about ten days,” Gowtham reveals, adding that it was a tightrope to strike a balance between aesthetics and information with the design. And nothing better than an auto to clinch the deal. “The auto is a flavour of Chennai. What better way to drive home such a message,” he signs off.","Artist Gowtham has transformed his auto into a 'vaccine auto' in Chennai, collaborating with the city's corporation to spread vaccine awareness. The three-wheeler features vials and injections, debunking myths and helping with vaccine bookings. An accompanying speaker blasts information about vaccines as the auto travels through the city's zones. The project aims to address hesitancy and fear surrounding vaccination, with a focus on practical information like CoWin registration and dose intervals. The vehicle, made from recycled materials, serves as a creative and engaging platform to educate the public, blending aesthetics with essential health messaging.",Health and Wellness,2021-06-29 00:00:00
Let there be light,"Diwali spans a five-day celebration, commencing from Dhanteras and culminating with Bhai Dooj. The festivities vary across the diverse regions of India, with unique customs and traditions observed. NT BUZZ highlights the multitude of ways Diwali is joyously observed KALYANI JHA | NT BUZZ Diwali, also known as Deepawali, unfolds its splendour 20 days after Dussehra, igniting a nationwide celebration marked by unwavering fervour and joy. Beyond the glitz of markets adorned with lanterns, ‘akash kandil’, and idols of Lakshmi and Ganesh, Diwali transcends regional distinctions to weave a rich tapestry of diverse celebrations. ‘Diwali Ki Safai’ The famous phrase ‘Diwali Ki Safai’, akin to a deep cleaning, takes centre stage as households and shops embark on a thorough cleansing spree. This is done to prepare for the arrival of the Goddess of Wealth and Well-being, Lakshmi. This annual ritual involves meticulous cleaning, painting, and decorating with lights and earthen lamps, symbolising the welcoming of prosperity and auspiciousness. Dhanteras: A prelude to radiance Two days before Diwali, the festivities kick off with Dhanteras, a day considered auspicious for buying gold or silver. Beyond material wealth, it symbolises a celebration of cleanliness, with people investing in brooms, associated with Goddess Lakshmi. Simultaneously, those in the medical profession honour Lord Dhanvantari, the physician of the gods and the father of ayurveda. Choti Diwali: Vanquishing darkness Choti Diwali, also known as Narak Chaturdashi, commemorates the defeat of the demon Narak by Lord Krishna. In certain regions, the fierce Goddess Kali is worshipped on this day, as she is believed to have slain this demon. Lighting an earthen lamp for Yama (the God of death) symbolises a prayer for the longevity of family members. Goddess Lakshmi and the quiescent Vishnu Contrary to common belief, during Diwali, Goddess Lakshmi is worshipped alongside Ganesha, not Vishnu, as Vishnu is said to be in a state of slumber. The significance of lighting numerous diyas during this period is rooted in the darkening days of the year, symbolising the triumph of light over darkness. A continuation of joy Following the luminous spectacle of Diwali, various regions in northern India usher in additional festivities. Bhaiyyadooj sees sisters praying for the well-being of their brothers, while Annakut or Goverdhan Puja involves offering 56 preparations to express gratitude for the lifting the Govardhan mountain. In Gujarat, Saal Mubarak or Bestu Varsh heralds the New Year, with businesses conducting Chopdapujan, worshiping account books for a prosperous financial cycle ahead. The Kayasth community celebrates Chitragupta Puja, venerating the pen and ink that meticulously record people’s lives and deeds. As the echoes of Diwali begin to faint, the celebrations continue to weave a bond of cultural richness, blending tradition, spirituality, and communal joy into the vibrant mosaic of India’s festival of lights.","Diwali spans five days, from Dhanteras to Bhai Dooj, celebrated across India with unique rituals. 'Diwali Ki Safai' initiates deep cleaning to welcome prosperity. Dhanteras signifies wealth, Choti Diwali vanquishes darkness, and Diwali worships Lakshmi. Post-Diwali, various regional celebrations continue, bonding communities through tradition and joy.",Human Interest,2023-11-11 00:00:00
"Tatas, Aircel only takers for MTNL 3G airwaves","NEW DELHI: Tata Teleservices and Aircel are poised to bag third-generation spectrum in the lucrative Delhi and Mumbai metros as they are the only bidders for MTNL’s offer to share its 3G network with two firms that pay the highest price. Aircel had won 3G airwaves in 13 circles and Tata Teleservices in nine when these frequencies were auctioned last year, but both these companies had failed to bag spectrum in Delhi and Mumbai. They had lost out to the country’s three largest mobile phone companies by both revenues and customers—Bharti Airtel, Reliance Communications and Vodafone Essar—in these metro cities, which are estimated to account for a fifth of the mobile industry’s revenues. MTNL had set `1,400 crore as the base price per operator when inviting bids from other telecom service providers to use its 3G frequencies, which enable services such as video calling and high-speed internet on phones. The state-owned operator will make a minimum of `2,800 crore from this deal. “The financial bids of both Tata Teleservices and Aircel will be opened in January—it is possible that the bid amount may be comparatively higher than the base price,” a top MTNL executive with direct knowledge of the development told ET. “There is also a revenue-share component—this depends on the type of 3G service offered—for instance, there are different slabs for voice and video calls, high-speed internet and other data services,” this executive added. Both Tata Teleservices and Aircel declined to comment, but a top executive from one of these companies confirmed that they were the only mobile phone companies to have submitted bids to MTNL. Talks on for roaming alliances All the six private players that won 3G airwaves are in talks with each other for strategic roaming alliances to offer these high-end services across the country. Such alliances have been made necessary since no player had won pan-India 3G airwaves during the auctions. So far, only two private operators—Reliance Communications and Tata Teleservices—have launched 3G services. The deal also involves the winners sharing 3G airwaves outside these metro cities with MTNL when the latter’s customers are on roaming. Between Aircel and Tata Teleservices, the duo jointly has 3G airwaves in all circles except Himachal Pradesh. Put simply, the deal will also enable MTNL to offer third-generation services on a pan-India level, except in Himachal Pradesh, for which it is in talks with BSNL.","Tata Teleservices and Aircel are set to acquire 3G spectrum in Delhi and Mumbai from MTNL, being the sole bidders to share its network. With base prices of ₹1,400 crore per operator, MTNL expects at least ₹2,800 crore. Talks for strategic alliances among winners aim to offer nationwide 3G services.",Technology and Gadgets,2011-01-01 00:00:00
