"Delhi-Mumbai Expressway Fully Operational, Cuts Travel Time to 12","The 1,386-km Delhi-Mumbai Expressway opened fully, reducing travel time from 24 to 12 hours. The ₹1 lakh crore project features EV charging stations, smart tolls, and 8 lanes. Nitin Gadkari said it will boost logistics and reduce carbon emissions by 30%.","India’s longest expressway, the 1,386-km Delhi-Mumbai corridor, is now fully operational, slashing travel time by half to just 12 hours. The ₹1 lakh crore project includes futuristic features like electric vehicle charging stations and AI-powered tolls. Road Transport Minister Nitin Gadkari highlighted its potential to transform freight logistics and reduce emissions. This infrastructure marvel is expected to spur economic growth across five states.",Infrastructure,2025-01-20 00:00:00
SAIL: Investors may have to wait boost in share price,"The stock of Steel authority of India (SAIL) has fallen more than 11% after its September quarter results, as the company disappointed the Street with dismal financial numbers. It reported one-third decrease in its net profit compared to the year-ago quarter. In the next quarter, however, higher steel prices in the past two months and lower raw material costs may offer some solace to the company. SAIL saw an 8-percentage point decrease in its operating margin in the September quarter from a year ago as the company struggled with higher raw material costs and employee expense for the second consecutive quarter. A higher coking coal price was the dampener for the company as it is mainly dependent on outside suppliers like Coal India for this. However in the prevailing quarter, coking coal prices have come down 10%, which will ease out some concern for the company in terms profitability in this quarter. It had faced headwinds due to its high inventory. It had to give discounts to sell the inventory that got accumulated in the first quarter. This is directly visible from a 15% fall in realisation sequentially. Inventory levels are still high and this trend is expected to continue in the coming quarter. SAIL is currently firming up a capex worth Rs 12,250 crore for FY11. The company, however, is struggling to complete its expansion projects on time. The commissioning of 2.4-million tonne per annum blast furnace expansion at Burnpur is getting delayed by six months. The company, on the other hand, has commissioned a blast furnace at BSP after the breakdown in August 2010. This recommissioning will help the company increase its production this quarter. While new capacities and focus on valueadded products might improve SAIL's production in the future, the company however is dependent on the domestic demand to sell its production. Global steel production increased 3.5% year on year in September despite a drop in Chinese output. According to world steel projections, demand would grow more than 13% in FY10, followed by 6% in FY11. Indian steel demand is expected to grow 12% over FY10-12 due to the planned infrastructure investment by the government and a rebound in capex. The company may post better results in the December quarter helped by higher steel prices, lower raw material costs and increased demand after the seasonally weak September quarter. However, investors may have to wait for a major boost in its share price until new capacities go on stream.","Steel Authority of India (SAIL) stock fell over 11% following disappointing September quarter results with a one-third decrease in net profit. Higher raw material costs, reduced operating margins, and high inventory levels contributed to the slump. However, falling coking coal prices, improved steel prices, and expected growth in domestic steel demand may offer some recovery in the December quarter.",Business and Finance,2010-11-19 00:00:00
