China effect lifts colour TV exports,"NEW DELHI: China''s loss could be India''s gain. Indian CTV manufacturers â€” facing a raw deal at home thanks to aggressive competition from Korean chaebols LG and Samsung â€” may have finally found a growth opportunity. Thanks to trade barriers in the US against Chinese imports, Indian CTV manufacturers â€” from Videocon to Onida to BPL â€” are getting a foothold in the lucrative, $100-billion home electronics market in the US. US has imposed anti-dumping duties of up to 78.45% on CTVs from China,threatened by surging Chinese exports. Exports of 21-inch and larger CTVs from China to the US rose from 56,295 in 2001 to nearly 1.76 million last year, threatening manufacturing jobs across the US. Videocon has made the first move by exporting 20-inches and 21-inches flat CTVs priced at about $100 each, after enquiries began coming a couple of months back, says VN Dhoot, the company''s CMD. To begin with, Videocon is targeting exports of 5 lakh units a year to the US. ""The US market is obviously lucrative. Our CTV exports to Italy and West Asia put together account for about 3 lakh units a year,"" says Dhoot. For Onida, which exports CTVs to Dubai, the US is a long-term and interesting opportunity for exports, says G Sundar, COO. CTV exports account for 10% of Onida''s sales. BPL, which has been exporting to Europe all along, is actively exploring the US market, says Manmohan Ganesh of BPL. ""We have exported colour monitors to the US in the past, but CTVs is definitely on the agenda now in the backdrop of anti-dumping duties in the US against China,"" says Ganesh. Analysts say for Onida which has stabilised, and Videocon, which has brand presence through Sansui, move is a growth opportunity for supplementing domestic sales. But for BPL, it could be only hope. ""Exports to US could possibly be the last survival strategy BPL is left with, considering that its market share in CTVs has plummeted to 5-6%,"" say analysts. LG and Samsung together control close to 35% of the domestic CTV market, estimated at over 7-million-units-a-year and growing at about 12% annually. While LG leads with a market share of about 17-18%, Samsung is at the second slot with a share of close to 15% share. Onida''s share, at No 3, is about 12%, Sansui''s share is in the region of 10-11% and Videocon is at about 9%.","The news discusses how Indian consumer television (CTV) manufacturers are finding an opportunity in the US market due to trade barriers against Chinese imports. With anti-dumping duties imposed on Chinese CTVs, companies like Videocon, Onida, and BPL are eyeing the lucrative US home electronics market. Videocon has already initiated exports, targeting 5 lakh units annually. Onida sees it as a long-term opportunity, while BPL views it as a survival strategy amidst declining market share domestically. The dominance of Korean companies LG and Samsung in the Indian CTV market is also highlighted.",Business and Finance,2004-05-01 00:00:00
