) called by the Sabarimala Karama Samithi and supported by the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP). There were sporadic clashes reported in different areas, including Ponkunnam, Thalayolaparambu, and Pampady. Incidents included stone-throwing at a supermarket, damage to political party flags and boards, and injuries to two BJP workers during a rally. To prevent disturbances, the police had detained some BJP and Sangh Parivar leaders the previous evening. The strike disrupted daily life as private buses and autorickshaws remained off the road, while only 25 special bus services operated by KSRTC were available. The situation returned to normal after 6 p.m., but Sabarimala pilgrims, particularly those arriving by train from other states, faced difficulties due to a lack of transportation. Additionally, all commercial establishments, including restaurants, were closed. The hartal had a significant impact on Erumely, which is typically exempt from such protests during the Sabarimala pilgrimage season. While a few KSRTC services to Sabarimala operated in the morning, businesses in the temple town were forced to close. Some groups, like DYFI workers, offered food and water to Sabarimala pilgrims and organized a rally against the strike in Manarcaud.",Local News,2019-01-03 00:00:00
