EARTHQUAKE PREPAREDNESS IN THE NORTHEAST STATES AND HIMALAYAN REGION,"The Himalayan region, which falls under the Seismic Zone IV and V, is a tectonically active region and the region has experienced strong earthquakes several times. The convergence of the Indian and Eurasian plates in the Himalayan region creates two subduction zones, making it seismically active. Research show that over 59% of India’s landmass is prone to earthquake and fall under various seismic zones. Within India, the Himalayan regions are at high risk of seismic activities and prone to earthquake. Increasing Seismic Activities For over 700 years, the region has been under tectonic stress and enough strains have been accumulated to trigger strong earthquakes that can have serious impact on the lives of millions. Over the past three decades, there has been an increase in earthquake frequency, indicating continuous tectonic activity. A study of seismic activities in the Himalayan region show a sharp spike in the frequency of earthquakes after 2000. Data from 1960-70 shows about 100 earthquakes per year in the Himalayan region, but after 2000, the frequency has gone up to 500-600 earthquakes of varying intensity. Some of the most devastating earthquakes in the Himalayan region and India over the past 150 years are: - 1897 (Shillong) – 8.0 magnitude, more than 1500 people dead - 1905 (Kangra) – 7.8 magnitude, more than 20000 people dead - 1934 (Nepal) – 8.0 magnitude, between 6000 – 10000 people dead - 1935 (Quetta) – 7.7 magnitude, between 30,000–60,000 people dead - 1950 (Assam) – 8.6 magnitude, between 1500 – 3000 people dead - 1991 Uttarkashi – 6.8 magnitude, about 2000 people dead - 1993 (Latur) – 6.2 magnitude, over 9000 people dead - 2001 (Gujarat) – 7.7 magnitude, about 20000 people dead - 2005 (Kashmir) – 7.6 magnitude, about 88000 people dead - 2011 (Sikkim) – 6.9 magnitude, over 100 people dead - 2015 (Nepal) – 7.8 magnitude, about 10000 people dead - 2023 (Nepal) – about 6.0 magnitude, over 150 people dead Apart from the loss of lives, the earthquakes have caused huge loss of properties, and in many cases, triggered other natural disasters like landslides, rockfalls, liquefaction, fires, flooding, and glacial lake outbursts. Natural disasters, such as earthquakes, present unforeseen challenges, testing our preparedness in ways often overlooked. In any natural disaster, emergency services get overwhelmed, and are many times unable to respond effectively during such events. Despite all warnings and red flags by scientists, the earthquake of April 25, 2015 in Nepal, caught experts and inhabitants off guard, revealing a lack of adequate preparation. The very recent earthquake of Nov 3, 2023 in Nepal destroyed 11,000 houses affecting around 14,000 families and caused 157 fatalities.","The Himalayan region, a tectonically active region, has experienced strong earthquakes several times due to the convergence of Indian and Eurasian plates. Over 59% of India's landmass is prone to earthquakes and falls under various seismic zones. Over 700 years, the region has been under tectonic stress, triggering strong earthquakes that can have serious impacts on millions of lives. Over the past three decades, earthquake frequency has increased, with a sharp spike after 2000. The most devastating earthquakes in the Himalayan region and India over the past 150 years include 1897 (Shillong), 1905 (Kangra), 1934 (Nepal), 1935 (Quetta), 1950 (Assam), 1991 (Uttarkashi), 1993 (Latur), 2001 (Gujarat), 2005 (Kashmir), 2011 (Sikkim), 2015 (Nepal), and 2023 (Nepal). Natural disasters present unforeseen challenges, testing our preparedness and emergency services' ability to respond effectively.",Environment,2023-12-18 00:00:00
