s for EVs to make up 15 per cent of its sales, with hybrids at 25 per cent, and the remaining 60 per cent divided among CNG, biofuels, and internal combustion engines.","Maruti Suzuki's stock surged over 5% on Tuesday, July 9, following Uttar Pradesh government's decision to waive registration fees for strong hybrid electric vehicles (HEVs) and plug-in hybrid electric vehicles (PHEVs). As of 12:36 pm IST, the company's shares were trading at Rs 12,833.85, up by 6.74%. HEVs and PHEVs differ primarily in their battery systems, with PHEVs having larger batteries that can be charged externally, while HEVs combine internal combustion engines with smaller batteries. Maruti Suzuki, a key player in the electric vehicle (EV) sector, stands to benefit significantly from this policy change. Their popular models like the Grand Vitara SUV and Invicto MPV, equipped with hybrid technology, will directly benefit from the waiver. For instance, the Grand Vitara features a hybrid powertrain combining a 1.5-litre petrol engine with an electric motor, while the Invicto MPV is a hybrid version of the Toyota Innova Hycross, boasting a 2.0-litre petrol engine with e-CVT transmission and 186PS combined system power. Looking ahead, Maruti Suzuki plans to introduce new electric and hybrid vehicles, starting with Battery Electric Vehicles (BEVs) from 2024, featuring a mid-SUV model with a range of 550 km on a 60 kWh battery. By 2030-31, the company aims for EVs to constitute 15% of its sales, with hybrids at 25%, while the remaining 60% will include CNG, biofuels, and internal combustion engines.",Business and Finance,2024-07-09 00:00:00
