Govt tells airlines to train pilots to operate in foggy conditions,"When you see from the window of your stranded plane on a foggy, winter morning that another aircraft is taxiing to take off, don't feel bad. For the take-off permission is given only to those pilots who have undergone CAT-IIIB training to fly in foggy conditions.""I often get phone calls from MPs complaining why their flights are being delayed whereas some other aircraft take off,"" civil aviation minister Praful Patel told the Lok Sabha on Thursday. Patel said that though the airlines have been told to provide their pilots adequate training to operate in foggy conditions, there is no proposal to make CAT-IIIB mandatory. ""The problem of dense fog is unique only to certain parts of the country; there is no need to make CAT-IIIB compulsory,"" he said. Patel explained that flight schedules of domestic operators to and from fog-covered airports was made on the basis of the availability of specially trained pilots and suitable aircraft with the airlines operating on those routes. According to civil aviation sources, some of the airlines have been reluctant to give their pilots the highly expensive CAT-IIIB training because fogs on an average last for about a fortnight in the winter. Replying to another question, Patel said that his ministry had not received any proposal from an international consultancy to develop non-operational airports in the country. He, however, said that a pre-feasibility study had been planned for operationalising 326 airports belonging to the state governments, defence authorities and private sectors around the country. This would give a boost to air connectivity in remote areas, he said.","Civil Aviation Minister Praful Patel addressed delays in foggy conditions, stating that only pilots trained in CAT-IIIB are permitted takeoff. He noted MPs' complaints about flight delays, emphasizing the importance of specialized training. While there's no mandate for CAT-IIIB training, flight schedules depend on trained pilots and suitable aircraft. Patel dismissed proposals to make CAT-IIIB mandatory, citing localized fog issues. Regarding airport development, he mentioned a pre-feasibility study for 326 non-operational airports to enhance air connectivity in remote areas. No proposals from international consultancies were received for this purpose.",Business and Finance,2008-12-19 00:00:00
