"Lawyers want RBI to plug gap, block foreign companies’ entry","MUMBAI: Bar Council of Delhi (BCD) has asked the government to direct the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) to plug what it called a loophole in its March 29 directive “which may lead to the backdoor entry of foreign law firms in India.” The lawyers’ body is of the view that the RBI’s direction, as well as an amendment to Special Economic Zone (SEZ) Rules in India, could be used by foreign law firms. In a letter to the Prime Minister on July 29, the BCD said the central bank’s March 29 directive said that for the establishment of the branch office, liaison office, project office or any other place of business in India, foreign entities rendering professional or consultancy services can operate after the RBI grants them an approval under the Foreign Exchange Management and Regulation Act. “We have serious objection to the decision to permit foreign law firms in Special Economic Zones (SEZ) area in India unilaterally without the concurrence of the parent body entrusted with the responsibility of the legal profession in India,” said the BCD in its fourpage letter. “The decision to permit foreign law firms to open an office in the SEZ area in India, being highly arbitrary, is uncalled for and contrary to the interest of the legal fraternity in India has wider implications.” On January 3, 2017, the government brought an amendment in the SEZ Rules which allowed foreign legal and accountancy services to operate from SEZs. “In the Special Economic Zones Rules, 2006, in Rule 76, for the words ‘professional services (excluding legal services and accounting) rental/leasing services without operators’, the words ‘professional services, rental/leasing services without operators’ shall be substituted,” said the amendment. “We want the government to direct the RBI to withdraw the ‘Master Directions’ and also the amendment of rule 76 of SEZ Rules in so far as they relate to the legal profession directly or indirectly,” said KC Mittal, chairman of the BCD. The BCD has also directed the Big Four audit and consulting firms not to offer legal services in India. In May, BCD had directed lawyers affiliated with KPMG, Price WaterhouseCoopers (PWC), EY and Deloitte India to refrain from practising law until further order. BCD took up the complaint filed by the apex body of the law firms, Society of Indian Law Firms (SILF) against major audit and accounting firms practising law. Now, the BCD is expected to hear the matter further on August 23.","The Bar Council of Delhi (BCD) has urged the government to instruct the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) to close a loophole in a March 29 directive that could allow foreign law firms to operate in India. The directive permits foreign entities offering professional or consultancy services to establish business offices in India with RBI approval. BCD's July 29 letter to the Prime Minister contends that this, along with an amendment to Special Economic Zone (SEZ) Rules, could enable foreign law firms to enter India, which BCD claims is against the interests of Indian legal professionals. The BCD demands the withdrawal of both the RBI directive and the SEZ rule amendment and has also prohibited the Big Four audit firms from providing legal services in India. The issue, prompted by a complaint from the Society of Indian Law Firms (SILF), will be further addressed on August 23.",Crime and Justice,2019-08-03 00:00:00
"Samsung unveils Galaxy A35, Galaxy A55 with flagship camera features: Price starts at Rs 30,999","Samsung on Monday announced two new A series smartphones — Galaxy A55 and the Galaxy A35, the latest mid-tier 5G smartphones with four years of promised Android OS upgrades and five years of security updates. The company claims that the latest A series smartphones offer Galaxy’s flagship camera innovations. And, these are also the first set of Galaxy A series smartphones to offer Samsung Knox Vault security features. The Galaxy A35 is available in two storage options with the base model with 8 GB RAM and 128 GB storage priced at Rs 30,999 and the 256 GB variant costs Rs 33,999. The Galaxy A55 is available in three variants, where, the base model costs Rs 39,999 for the base model with 8 GB RAM and 128 GB storage, the 8 GB RAM and 256 GB variant costs Rs 42,999, and lastly, the 12 GB RAM and 256 GB variant is priced at Rs 45,999. The company is offering a flat Rs 3,000 discount on all the models (for HDFC, OneCard, and IDFC First Bank card users), which brings down the effective price of Galaxy A35 to Rs 27,999 and the effective price of Galaxy A55 comes down to Rs 36,999. Both smartphones will be available for purchase starting March 14. As of now, the company has not shared any details regarding the pricing or the availability of the Galaxy A35 and the Galaxy A55 in India, which will be unveiled on March 14. Galaxy A55Galaxy A55 (Image credit: Samsung) TM Roh, President and Head of Mobile eXperience Business at Samsung Electronics said: “We are excited to open up even more possibilities on the Galaxy A series this year, including offering Samsung Knox Vault for the first time on this lineup. We’re proud to enable Galaxy A series users to safely and reliably enjoy outstanding mobile experiences.” While they look quite identical to each other and also offer an IP67 rating against water and dust, the Galaxy A55 comes with a metal frame, while the Galaxy A35 features a plastic frame. Festive offer Both smartphones come with a 6.6-inch FHD+ resolution display with 120Hz refresh rate and an optical in-display fingerprint sensor, protected by Gorilla Glass Victus+. While the more premium Galaxy A55 is powered by the Exynos 1480 SoC, the Galaxy A35 makes use of the Exynos 1380 that powered the Galaxy A54 (review). Both smartphones offer 8 GB RAM and 128/256 GB of storage, and out-of-the-box, these devices ship with Android 14-based OneUI 6.1 and will receive updates up to Android 18. However, unlike the Galaxy S24 series, these smartphones do not offer any AI-related features. Galaxy A35Galaxy A35 (Image credit: Samsung) The Galaxy A55 has a triple camera setup with a 50 MP primary sensor, a 12 MP ultra-wide angle lens, and a 5 MP macro lens. Similarly, the Galaxy A35 has a 50 MP main camera, an 8 MP ultra-wide angle lens, and a 5 MP macro lens. While the Galaxy A55 offers a 32 MP selfie camera, the Galaxy A35 has a 13 MP front-facing camera. In terms of features, these devices offer optical image stabilization (OIS) and video digital image stabilization (VDIS), Night Portrait mode, 12-bit HDR video, and enhanced Nightography features, powered by advanced AI Image Signal Processing (ISP). Samsung has confirmed that accessories like Galaxy Fit3, Galaxy Watch6, and the Galaxy Buds SE are compatible with the Galaxy A55 and the Galaxy A35 and offer capabilities like auto connect and auto switch for added convenience. Both smartphones offer a 5,000 mAh battery with support for 25W fast charging.","Samsung has announced two new A series smartphones, the Galaxy A55 and the Galaxy A35, which are mid-tier 5G devices with four years of promised Android OS upgrades and five years of security updates. The A35 comes in two storage options, with the base model priced at Rs 30,999 and the 256 GB variant at Rs 33,999. The Galaxy A55 is available in three variants, with the base model priced at Rs 39,999, the 8 GB RAM and 128 GB variant at Rs 42,999, and the 12 GB RAM and 256 GB variant at Rs 45,999. Samsung is offering a flat Rs 3,000 discount on all models, bringing the A35's effective price to Rs 27,999 and the A55's to Rs 36,999. Both smartphones feature a 6.6-inch FHD+ resolution display, an optical in-display fingerprint sensor, and Android 14-based OneUI 6.1. They also offer optical image stabilization, video digital image stabilization, Night Portrait mode, 12-bit HDR video, and enhanced Nightography features powered by advanced AI Image Signal Processing.",Technology and Gadgets,2024-03-14 00:00:00
