City breathes easy as unseasonal rain improves air quality,"Mumbai: A day after unseasonal showers, the city breathed easy as the overall air quality index (AQI) dropped to 85 on Wednesday. On Tuesday night, several parts of Mumbai, especially the suburbs, witnessed brief spells of rain. As a result, a majority of the 25 AQI stations of the Maharashtra Pollution Control Board recorded an AQI of below 100 on Wednesday. The lowest AQI was recorded in Mulund (60), followed by Kandivli (61) and Colaba (62). Across the Mumbai Metropolitan Region, the lowest AQI was recorded in Vasai (55). AQI is based on the concentration of carcinogenic particulate matter (PM2.5) in air. AQI levels for PM2.5 below 50 are considered ‘good’, 50-99 ‘satisfactory’, 100-199 ‘moderate’, above 200 ‘poor’, above 300 ‘very poor’, above 400 ‘severe’ and above 500 ‘very severe’. BMC chief I S Chahal said the drop in AQI is a good sign for the city. In October 2023, when AQI levels had crossed the 300-mark, BMC had undertaken a slew of measures to ensure that dust pollution was controlled. It had released 27 guidelines to all worksites, including government projects, to comply within 30 days. On Wednesday, the Colaba and Santacruz weather statio-ns recorded daytime temperatures of 32 degrees Celsius and 31.9 degrees Celsius, respectively, and minimum temperatures of 23 degrees Celsius and 22.3 degrees Celsius, respectively. The IMD has forecast that on Thursday, maximum and minimum temperatures will be around 31 degrees C and 22 degrees C, respectively. tnn","Following unseasonal showers, Mumbai's air quality improved with the overall air quality index (AQI) dropping to 85 on Wednesday. Most AQI stations recorded levels below 100, with Mulund, Kandivli, and Colaba among the lowest. The AQI is based on PM2.5 concentration, with levels below 50 considered 'good.' BMC chief I S Chahal noted the drop in AQI as a positive development. The IMD forecasted maximum and minimum temperatures of around 31°C and 22°C, respectively, for Thursday.",Environment,2024-01-11 00:00:00
Technology alone won't improve lives: Premji,"bangalore: it is a myth that technology itself improves the quality of life. only if such technology is made available to the majority and used imaginatively for the well-being of society can people appreciate its importance, azim premji, chairman of azim premji foundation said here on wednesday. delivering the keynote address at a consultative workshop on role of technology in elementary education organised by the azim premji foundation, he said there was a growing demand by parents that children should learn english language and computers. the human development report 2001 has established that there is a direct correlation between the technology achievement index and the human development index of the country. speaking on the role of it in elementary education as one of the key facilitators in achieving universalisation of elementary education, premji said: ``there is a huge potential to impact the quality of learning through imaginative usage of education contests that can effectively supplement the efforts of teachers. there is a need to develop education software content with a context base which is indian and rural,'' he said. eductionists should give due importance to the aspirations of vast majority of parents as well as the demands and expecations of children while evolving a perspective on elementary education. ``we also need to be aware of the demands that would emerge ten years later in terms of employment competencies and societal pressure of utilising it in every walk of life. very clearly, the definition of literacy would change to include it literacy,'' premji told the gathering which comprised officials from different states and ngos. universalisation of elementary education is not the responsibility of the government alone but all citizens. ``the task before us is mammoth and there is no way we can achieve this task without the active participation and cooperation of not only the government but every member of the society,'' he said. the apf was committed to facilitate the process of universalisation of elementary education in a rime bound and result oriented manner. ``for this, we are willing to commit resources to supplement the efforts of the government and other agencies,'' premji explained. making a presentation on the community learning centre initiative, apf executive group member c.v. madhukar said a pilot project was being carried out on the effective use of it infurthering elementary education. the project was being carried out in 34 community learning centres set up by the apf.","Azim Premji, Chairman of Azim Premji Foundation, addressed a workshop on the role of technology in elementary education in Bangalore. Premji emphasized that technology's impact on quality of life lies in its imaginative use for societal well-being and universal access. He highlighted the growing demand for English and computer education. Acknowledging the correlation between the technology achievement index and human development index, he stressed the need for Indian and rural-centric educational software. Premji urged educationists to consider parental aspirations and evolving employment competencies. Emphasizing collective responsibility for universalizing elementary education, he pledged the foundation's support and presented a pilot project on IT's role in education.",Education,2002-01-23 00:00:00
Swachh a pity: 10 of 21 ‘smart’ toilets in Pune not operational,"Toilets are not functioning as PMC is not providing water, says MLA Siddharth Shirole With the aim of providing clean and hygienic public toilets, former Pune MP Anil Shirole, in 2018, had initiated a project for installation of state-of-the-art, automatic, smart toilet facilities in the city. Shirole spent Rs 2 crore from his MP development fund to erect 21 smart toilets in the city. However, after they were installed, 10 of the 21 smart toilets are not operational as per Right to Information (RTI) activist Abhijeet Baravkar. Baravkar who filed an RTI application seeking information regarding the smart toilets in the city said that the Pune Municipal Corporation (PMC) on February 20, confirmed that 10 toilets are not functioning. “I have been following up this issue for the past one year. A few months after the smart toilets were installed they became non-operational and are not used by the public. The ones that are operational are also not being utilised fully. On one hand the PMC is looking to rank No. 1 under the Swachh Survekshan ranking, and on the other hand the civic body is not in a position to maintain the facility,” said Baravkar. PMC solid waste management department’s executive engineer Sudhir Chavan said that he has issued a letter to the concerned contractor to repair the toilets. However, Baravkar claimed that despite the letter, none of the toilets have been repaired. Siddharth Shirole, member of legislative assembly (MLA) and son of Anil Shirole said, “It is true that some smart toilets are not operational. It is the PMC’s responsibility to carry out the maintenance of these toilets. The civic body must ensure that the concerned contractor carries out maintenance on a regular basis. Most of the smart toilets are not functioning as PMC is not providing water.” Vinay Parge, an IT employee who has used the smart toilet said, “Smart toilets are a good concept, the only problem is lack of maintenance. It is not fair to only blame the PMC, as the residents are also equally responsible. Some residents spit in the areas surrounding the toilets, in such cases the civic body is helpless. Rs 2 crore plan gets flushed... down the drain Smart toilets work on a human sensor mechanism. It self-flushes before and after use. After every few uses, the floors are automatically flushed clean 21: Total No. of smart toilets in Pune 10: Non-operational 11: Operational Clean up your act Non-operational toilets No. of smart toilets location Reason 2 Senapati Bapat road No water 2 Model Colony No water 2 Nilayam Bridge, Swargate Coin box broken 2 Taljai Tekadi No water 2 Vimannagar Coin box broken Operational toilets No. of smart toilets location 3 Fergusson College road 2 Jungli Maharaj road 2 Hirwe Garden, Deccan Gymkhana 2 Wadia College, Bund Garden road 2 Rajaram Bridge, Vittahlawdadi Toilets: What’s so ‘smart’ about it? - Smart toilets are prefabricated structures made from stainless steel - Automatic system for access, flushing and cleaning the floor - Users insert a coin in specified slot to open door. The user can insert a coin of any denomination to use the e-toilet - Once door opens, sensor-based light system automatically turns on - Toilet automatically flushes before and after use with guided audio commands for user - Mechanised system cleans the toilet platform after every few users - User does not get access to toilet if it is not cleaned","In 2018, former Pune MP Anil Shirole initiated a project to install state-of-the-art smart toilets in the city, spending Rs 2 crore from his MP development fund. However, an RTI application filed by activist Abhijeet Baravkar revealed that 10 out of the 21 installed smart toilets are not operational. Despite a letter issued by the Pune Municipal Corporation (PMC) to the contractor for repairs, no action has been taken. MLA Siddharth Shirole, son of Anil Shirole, blamed PMC for failing to maintain the toilets, specifically citing the lack of water supply as a key issue. Some residents also contribute to the problem by misusing the toilets, as mentioned by IT employee Vinay Parge. The smart toilets are designed with automatic flushing and cleaning systems, and are operated using a coin mechanism. The facilities were intended to provide clean, hygienic public toilets but have faced maintenance issues, with several locations reported to be non-functional due to broken coin boxes or lack of water.",Local News,2020-03-04 00:00:00
High-octane campaign ends for opening phase,"New Delhi : A high-octane campaign for the first and largest phase of the Lok Sabha elections closed on Wednesday with the National Democratic Alliance (NDA) and the Indian National Developmental Inclusive Alliance (INDIA) facing off against a vast swathe of constituencies across India, two days before the world’s largest democratic exercise kicked off. A total of 102 constituencies across 21 states and Union territories will vote on Friday to determine the fates of 1,625 candidates. The first phase of the polls saw Prime Minister Narendra Modi lead the campaign for the NDA, which is aiming to win 400 Lok Sabha seats in the seven-phase polls. He addressed 40 rallies across more than a dozen states, underlining his government’s Viksit Bharat (developed India) pitch, infrastructure push and ideological goals such as the abrogation of Article 370 and construction of the Ram Temple. He also lambasted the Opposition over dynasty politics, eating meat during a month considered holy by some Hindus, and misleading the public on the plans to alter the Constitution. He spent a majority of his time in the south and the east, where critical battles in Bihar, West Bengal and Tamil Nadu will likely determine if the BJP is able to reach its goal of 370 seats. “A new atmosphere is prevailing in the entire country as we celebrate the birth anniversary of Lord Ram in his own home after 500 years and this is a culmination of centuries of devotion and generations of sacrifice,” he said at a rally in Assam, where five seats go to the polls. The INDIA response was led by a patchwork group of leaders ranging from Congress leader Rahul Gandhi, West Bengal chief minister Mamata Banerjee, Samajwadi Party chief Akhilesh Yadav and Tamil Nadu chief minister MK Stalin. They questioned the government on unemployment and depressed wages, alleged that democracy was under threat and highlighted the incarceration of two sitting CMs – Delhi’s Arvind Kejriwal and Jharkhand’s Hemant Soren. “Sometimes they will scare you and give you bundles of money. Why are you afraid every day? Who will you be afraid of? If Modi somehow wins, there will be no democracy in the country. Who will save the country?” Banerjee asked in a rally. The first phase will see all seats from Tamil Nadu, Uttarakhand, Arunachal Pradesh, Mizoram, Nagaland, Meghalaya, Sikkim, Andaman and Nicobar, Lakshadweep and Puducherry go to the polls. The other six phases will take place over the next six weeks, with the results on June 4. Modi is seeking a historic third consecutive term, hoping to become only the second PM after Jawaharlal Nehru to achieve this feat. The largest chunk of seats will be in Tamil Nadu, where all 39 seats are going to the polls. The INDIA bloc holds 38 out of these seats and the Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam-led grouping in the state will hope for a repeat performance. Battling the ruling coalition is its traditional Dravidian rival, the All India Anna Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam, and a resurgent BJP that has put in enormous energy and resources into a state that is considered a bridge too far for the party. The AIADMK, which left the BJP alliance in 2023, targeted the DMK in the state and the BJP at the Centre for poor governance. Also in the race is Tamil nationalist S Seeman’s Naam Tamizhar Katchi (NTK) who in his fiery speeches campaigned for a corruption free Tamil Nadu. Around 61 million voters will decide the fate of 950 candidates. All five Lok Sabha seats in Uttarakhand, where the BJP and Congress are in direct contest, will also go to the polls. The BJP, which swept the state in 2014 and 2019, replaced three MPs. Modi addressed two rallies, home minister Amit Shah one, Uttar Pradesh chief minister Yogi Adityanath, who was born in Uttarkhand, two and Congress’s Priyanka Gandhi and Sachin Pilot covered three constituencies. The fate of 55 candidates will be decided by 16 million voters. Focus will also be on the 12 Lok Sabha seats in Rajasthan, where the other 13 will go to the polls in the next phase. The state will decide the fate of 131 candidates. The BJP had swept Rajasthan in 2019 and is contesting all seats. The Congress, on the other hand, is contesting 22 and left three for its alliance partners Rashtriya Loktantrik Party (RLP), Communist Party of India (Marxist) and Bharat Adivasi Party (BAP). Modi visited the state five times , Rahul Gandhi twice and Congress president Malliarjun Kharge once. On the last day of the campaign in Uttar Pradesh, which sends 80 members to the Lok Sabha, Congress leader Priyanka Gandhi Vadra and Samajwadi Party president Akhilesh Yadav – both partners in opposition’s INDIA bloc – addressed rallies in Saharanpur and Moradabad. The seats going to polls in the first phase on Friday are Saharanpur, Bijnor, Kairana, Muzaffarnagar, Nagina, Moradabad, Rampur, and Pilibhit. In Madhya Pradesh, six of the 29 Lok Sabha seats are going to polls. Among the slew of leaders who campaigned in the state, Modi addressed four rallies and Rahul Gandhi two. In Bihar, four seats are going to polls – Jamui, Nawada, Gaya and Aurangabad. Modi addressed rallies in three of the four constituencies. In fourth constituency, Aurangabad, Union home minister Amit Shah addressed a rally. All the four were won by the NDA in 2019. The INDIA bloc campaign was led by Tejaswhi Yadav of the RJD. In West Bengal, the BJP won all three seats in 2019. In the Northeast, 14 of the 25 Lok Sabha seats including five in Assam, which will go to polls. The last day of the campaign saw election rallies by Modi in Assam and Tripura, and by Banerjee in Assam’s Barak Valley. Prominent candidates who are contesting in the first phase include BJP’s former Assam chief minister and incumbent Union minister Sarbananda Sonowal (Dibrugarh), Union minister Kiren Rijiju (Arunachal West), former Tripura chief minister Biplab Kumar Deb (West Tripura), Congress’s deputy leader in Lok Sabha Gaurav Gogoi (Jorhat) and former Arunachal Pradesh chief minister Nabam Tuki (West Arunachal). Fifty of the 60 assembly seats in Arunachal Pradesh will also go to the polls, after the BJP won 10 seats unopposed. The votes will be counted together for all Lok Sabha and assembly seats on June 4.","The high-stakes Lok Sabha election kicks off with the first phase covering 102 constituencies across 21 states. PM Modi leads NDA's campaign emphasizing development and ideological goals. INDIA bloc, led by opposition leaders, highlights concerns over democracy and governance. Key battlegrounds include Tamil Nadu, Uttarakhand, Rajasthan, Uttar Pradesh, Bihar, and West Bengal.",Politics,2024-04-18 00:00:00
